SIMPLE: subside
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Subside
<hw>Sub*side"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Subsided</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Subsiding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>subsidere</ets>;
<ets>sub</ets> under, below + <ets>sidere</ets> to sit down, to settle;
akin to <ets>sedere</ets> to sit, E. <ets>sit</ets>. See
<er>Sit</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To sink or fall to the bottom; to
settle, as lees.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To tend downward; to become lower; to descend; to
sink.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Heaven's <xex>subsiding</xex> hill.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To fall into a state of quiet; to cease to rage; to
be calmed; to settle down; to become tranquil; to abate; <as>as, the sea
<ex>subsides</ex>; the tumults of war will <ex>subside</ex>; the fever
has <ex>subsided</ex></as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧In cases of danger, pride and
envy naturally <xex>subside</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>C.
Middleton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Abate</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Subsidency</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Subsidence</ent>⟦br⟧
